<TITLE> Stocks end higher for second day </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, August 27 (bdnews24.com)  Stocks posted gains for a second day, paced by a rise in banks, power and cement heavyweights. BRAC Bank led the upbeat Monday. "It appears that investor confidence has increased. New funds and new investors are also coming into the market," said Sharif Ataur Rahman, a market analyst. Bank stocks finished up, buoyed by rises in BRAC Bank, UCBL, National Bank, AB Bank and Pubali Bank. Market major BRAC Bank, the most traded issue, added 3.59 percent to Tk 994. State-run power generator DESCO, which touched a new high the previous day, fell 1.39 percent to Tk 1152.5. Power Grid Company of Bangladesh, second biggest share by market capitalisation, moved up 3.94 percent to Tk 593.25. Anticipation of high returns drove UCBL 5.67 percent up at Tk 4011.5. It earlier announced that it would hold its annual general meetings that had been pending from 1998. The cement sector finished mixed as Heidelberg Cement ended lower but Lafarge Surma gained. Heidelberg declined 0.83 percent to Tk 1215.25. Pharmaceuticals fell. The DGEN or general index added 20.73 points or 0.87 percent to close at 2398.41. The DSI or all-share price index gained 18.95 points or 0.95 percent to 2001.13. The DSE-20 blue chip index rose 19.29 points or 0.99 percent to finish at 1958.28. Of the issues traded, 93 gained, 86 lost and 21 held steady. A total of 10,288,126 shares worth Tk 1.66 billion changed hands. On the DSE, Rupali Insurance, 2nd ICB mutual fund and BOC topped the gainers. Information Services Network, 7th ICB MF and 8th ICB MF were the main losers. "It was an active market and finished upbeat building on the previous day's sentiment," said Yawer Sayeed, a senior analyst at AIMS of Bangladesh. All the major indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange edged up, spurred by a rise in bank and energy shares. On the CSE, 52 issues closed up, 50 dipped and 10 remained unchanged. A total of 1,028,736 shares worth Tk 162.50 million traded. bdn
